Globally, they attack more than 100 species of trees, according to Prof Marcus Byrne of the Zoology and Entomology department at South Africaâ€™s Wits University.The most common sign of attack is a noodle-like waste and sawdust mixture protruding from the trunk of attacked plants and fine sawdust surrounding the base of trees.Ambrosia beetles are mostly attracted to ethanol, a chemical that trees produce when they are stressed.Dr Moses Langat, a research scientist at the Royal Botanic Gardens in the UK, is coordinating research on its medicinal benefits.